In this work, we investigate the following weakly damped nonlinear suspension-bridge problem
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned} \left\{ \begin{array}{lcr} u_{tt}(x,y,t)+\Delta ^2 u(x,y,t) +\alpha(t) g(u_t(x,y,t))=0,\; {in} \;\Omega \times (0, \infty), \\{}
u(0,y,t)=u_{xx}(0,y,t)=u(\pi ,y,t)=u_{xx}(\pi ,y,t)=0,\;(y,t)\in (-d, d)\times (0, \infty), \\ u_{yy}(x,\pm d,t)+\sigma u_{xx}(x,\pm d, t)=0,\;(x,t)\in (0,\pi )\times (0, \infty), \\ u_{yyy}(x,\pm d,t)+(2-\sigma )u_{xxy}(x,\pm d, t)=0,\;(x,t)\in (0,\pi )\times (0, \infty),\ u(x,y,0)=u_0(x,y),\; u_t(x,y,0)=u_1(x,y),\; \text{ in } \;\Omega, \end{array} \right.
 \end{aligned}
 \end{equation*}
 where $ \Omega= (0, \pi) \times (-d, d) $, $g: \mathbb{R}\rightarrow \mathbb{R} $ and $\alpha: [0, +\infty) \rightarrow  (0, + \infty)$ are functions such that $\alpha$ is non-increasing and differentiable, $u$ is the vertical displacement of the bridge, and $\sigma$ is the Poisson ratio.

We use the multiplier method and the properties of the convex and establish an explicit and a general decay result for the solution energy of the problem. This decay result depends on the functions $\alpha$ and $g$ and is obtained without any restriction growth assumption on $g$ at the origin.

We consider $l^{\rm th}$-order linear fractional differential equations with constant coefficients
	\begin{equation*}\label{GenBesselEqnBeyond}
	D^{\alpha}u(x) + \lambda  D^\beta u(x)+ \sum_{i=0}^{m-2 }p_i D^{\alpha_i} u(x)=0, 
	\end{equation*}
where $\alpha>\beta>\alpha_{m-2}>\ldots>\alpha_1>\alpha_0=0$ and $l=\lceil{\alpha}\rceil$. 
The current theory requires  $\alpha-\beta\geq l-1$ for the existence of $l$ linearly independent solutions and, thus, at most one derivative may have order greater than one but all other derivatives must be between zero and one. We remove this essential restriction and elaborate the multi-sum fractional series approach to construct $l$ linearly independent solutions for constant coefficients and Riemann-Liouville and Caputo fractional derivatives of arbitrary orders.
